# ── Instagram feed configuration ───────────────────────────────────────
# Copy this file to `.env` for LOCAL development. In production (Vercel),
# set these in the host's dashboard instead — never commit real values.
# Without any of these, the site shows curated sample images automatically.


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# LOCAL DEVELOPMENT (quick + simple; token is only on your machine)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# The long-lived token, and "me" (or your numeric IG user id).
VITE_IG_ACCESS_TOKEN=
VITE_IG_USER_ID=me


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# PRODUCTION / DEPLOY (secure — token stays on the server, never exposed)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# In Vercel, set THESE THREE and leave VITE_IG_ACCESS_TOKEN blank/unset:
#
#   IG_ACCESS_TOKEN    = <long-lived token>   ← server-only, stays private
#   IG_USER_ID         = me                    ← server-only
#   VITE_IG_PROXY_URL  = /api/instagram        ← tells the site to use the proxy
#
# The frontend then calls /api/instagram (see api/instagram.js), which talks to
# Instagram from the server. The token is never sent to the browser.
#
# IMPORTANT: do NOT set VITE_IG_ACCESS_TOKEN in production — anything with a
# VITE_ prefix is baked into the public website. Use the un-prefixed
# IG_ACCESS_TOKEN so it lives only on the server.
# VITE_IG_PROXY_URL=
